    "reasoning": "Structured as satirical fiction with a named protagonist (Arthur), a clear arc of cognitive decline, and alternating narrative documents — but the corporate-dystopia satire carries an implicit argument about commodified consciousness."
  },
  "thematic_thrust": "A man surrenders his struggling mind to a subscription happiness implant and is erased, journal entry by entry.",
  "characters": {
    "Arthur P. L.": "narrator; voluntary NeuraBless implant recipient, self-described Joy-Pioneer",
    "Dr. Yuki Tanaka": "philosopher and cognitive researcher; Arthur's warning voice and last monitor",
    "NeuraBless™": "corporate neural-stimulation company; the antagonist system dissolving Arthur"
  },
  "voice_anchors": [
    {
      "nodeId": "6-2",
      "snippet": "We aren't just selling a product; we are curating the human soul.",
      "note": "Corporate euphemism at its most grotesque pitch: grandiose register masks the premise's horror."
    },
    {
      "nodeId": "6-23",
      "snippet": "Tanaka was crying. Why cry? Crying is a bug. NeuraBless™ is the fix.",
      "note": "Arthur's inverted moral logic enacted at the sentence level: the short declaratives perform the simplification the story describes."
    },
    {
      "nodeId": "6-48",
      "snippet": "the truth hurts, but the wire feels great",
      "note": "Closing tagline crystallizes the story's satirical thesis in a single antithesis."
    }
  ],
